Inspection and Registration of Deorais

Comprehensive surveys should be carried out to update the list of deoras across Maharashtra. Make a body-wise update of all deoras. Record the number of deoras and classify them by area. This survey will determine the deorai area and its extent. Forest boundaries need to be clearly demarcated, but should be flexible to accommodate future forest growth.
Member Secretary, Maharashtra State Biodiversity Board, Nagpur

table_trans: Creating a Geographic Map
GIS systems should be used to create geo-referenced maps of the updated inventory.
Member Secretary, Maharashtra State Biodiversity Board, Nagpur
Evaluation of Biodiversity

Conduct an in-depth biodiversity assessment of each Deorai, document the diversity, numeracy, and composition of the flora and fauna of the Deorai. Study ecological priorities in Deorai. Register rare, threatened, and endangered plant and animal species found in Deorai and take necessary measures for their conservation and conservation.
Member Secretary, Maharashtra State Biodiversity Board, Nagpur
Priorities by Environmental Importance

Using the data collected, each Deorai should be assessed for its ecological importance and sites prioritised for conservation and restoration efforts. Deorai should be prioritised on the basis of their biological importance, risks to the Deorai, etc.
Member Secretary, Maharashtra State Biodiversity Board, Nagpur
Field Verification
The data should be authenticated and updated by visiting each devarai and physically inspecting it using a questionnaire.
Principal Chief Conservator of Forests (Chief of Forest Force), Maharashtra State, Nagpur

Local Traditional Knowledge Register

Documentation of local and traditional knowledge on species identity, traditional uses, traditional management and conservation practices in Deorai. Public Biodiversity Records should also be updated.
Member Secretary, Maharashtra State Biodiversity Board, Nagpur
Legal protection

With a view to conserve and conserve the Deora, efforts should be made by the Forest Department to declare the area of the Deora as a Conservation Reserve or Community Reserve or Biodiversity Heritage Site by taking locals into confidence.
Principal Chief Conservator of Forests (Wildlife), Maharashtra State, Nagpur Member Secretary, Maharashtra State Biodiversity Board, Nagpur
Training for local communities.

Organize workshops and training sessions for local citizens, public representatives and forest officials to improve traditional management practices and incorporate modern conservation techniques. Training with the help of various rating agencies using various tools such as GIS, remote sensing, mobile applications, etc., and promote Deoraya conservation concepts in local languages.
Member Secretary, Maharashtra State Biodiversity Board, Nagpur
Research and Inspection
Research activities to assess the ecological, cultural and economic aspects of Deorai.

Funding and Implementation

The Maharashtra State Biodiversity Board will act as the nodal department for conservation of Deorai and the proposal for requisition of funds required for this will be submitted to the state government by the Maharashtra Biodiversity Board through the Additional Principal Chief Conservator of Forests (Budget, Planning and Development), Maharashtra State, Nagpur.
